1
00:00:01,260 --> 00:00:18,220
He shares our germs together. So we stay together, but boy, we are sick together. I don't feel so bad. I just don't sound too good. So you just sort of hang in there with me, and if the last few words of a sentence drop off, just, you know, look up, and I'll try and repeat that.

2
00:00:18,900 --> 00:00:21,600
But we're going to have a good time this morning because God's word is going to come alive.

3
00:00:21,680 --> 00:00:24,060
In my weakness, Jesus is still on top.

4
00:00:24,680 --> 00:00:26,520
So with that, let me just share a funny story.

5
00:00:26,600 --> 00:00:27,760
Some of you may have heard this.

6
00:00:28,570 --> 00:00:32,130
In my pastoral training at Fuller Seminary, I took a course,

7
00:00:32,780 --> 00:00:39,560
and I was a chaplain's intern at a county general over there in downtown L.A. for a course.

8
00:00:40,140 --> 00:00:43,920
So for 12 weeks, we met weekly at the hospital.

9
00:00:44,460 --> 00:00:48,040
We went to all the different wards, all the different dimensions of the hospital.

10
00:00:48,040 --> 00:00:54,340
went into pretty much everything, and we weren't so much training to be chaplains of hospitals

11
00:00:54,340 --> 00:00:58,680
as we were just learning all about life and death and bodies and machines

12
00:00:58,680 --> 00:01:01,760
so that we can work out the willies, if you know what I mean,

13
00:01:01,820 --> 00:01:05,700
so we can go to the hospital and minister to people and understand what's happening.

14
00:01:06,460 --> 00:01:09,900
And I will never forget many of those experiences, and if you ever have coffee with me,

15
00:01:09,920 --> 00:01:13,560
I'll tell you some pretty interesting stories about that, but I'll save those for later.

16
00:01:13,840 --> 00:01:16,560
But I want to share one this morning, and some of you may have heard this,

17
00:01:16,560 --> 00:01:18,120
but it just struck me so powerfully.

18
00:01:18,160 --> 00:01:19,160
I'll never forget this.

19
00:01:20,020 --> 00:01:21,780
He took us, there was only four of us,

20
00:01:22,860 --> 00:01:25,040
out to a cemetery and crematorium

21
00:01:25,040 --> 00:01:26,830
towards the end of the course

22
00:01:26,830 --> 00:01:29,270
to kind of show us those dimensions

23
00:01:29,270 --> 00:01:30,590
of the life experience.

24
00:01:31,530 --> 00:01:34,190
And so we met the gentleman who ran the crematorium

25
00:01:34,190 --> 00:01:35,390
and we saw some things there

26
00:01:35,390 --> 00:01:36,370
and I won't go into all of that,

27
00:01:36,470 --> 00:01:38,930
but we stepped outside and we looked at some

28
00:01:38,930 --> 00:01:41,130
caskets and various things

29
00:01:41,130 --> 00:01:43,750
and he was describing these different accoutrements.

30
00:01:44,810 --> 00:01:45,870
And somewhere in this,

31
00:01:45,870 --> 00:01:50,410
Phil Manley, the professor and the chaplain that was in charge of this experience

32
00:01:50,410 --> 00:01:54,360
kind of disappeared. And we were walking down with the curator

33
00:01:54,360 --> 00:01:58,200
of the cemetery there and he was showing us some things. And then he went back and he

34
00:01:58,200 --> 00:02:02,740
showed us the coffin and he talked about, you know, the cost and this and that.

35
00:02:02,800 --> 00:02:06,420
And then he opened it. At which point there was a body

36
00:02:06,420 --> 00:02:11,990
inside that came alive. Because Phil Manley, my

37
00:02:11,990 --> 00:02:16,780
professor and friend, was laying in the casket, came up and

38
00:02:16,780 --> 00:02:21,200
scared the living everything out of us.

39
00:02:22,510 --> 00:02:25,790
It takes a few seconds to realize there's a body and then who is it

40
00:02:25,790 --> 00:02:29,650
and suddenly as it sits up, we just about lost it.

41
00:02:30,590 --> 00:02:34,330
I will never forget that experience and he just, he never

42
00:02:34,330 --> 00:02:38,410
let us have the end of that one, looking at the blanched white faces

43
00:02:38,410 --> 00:02:42,390
of these young pastoral interns as he popped up from death.

44
00:02:43,130 --> 00:02:46,730
That was a funny encounter in the theme of death

45
00:02:46,730 --> 00:02:50,190
but obviously the discourse about death is actually very serious.

46
00:02:51,270 --> 00:02:54,070
And in all seriousness, when I read the newspaper often

47
00:02:54,070 --> 00:02:59,050
and I read the accounts of young people that perish in auto accidents

48
00:02:59,050 --> 00:03:01,950
as a result of their just fooling around

49
00:03:01,950 --> 00:03:07,540
and hear the grief in the families and the high schools

50
00:03:07,540 --> 00:03:09,700
as they struggle with that,

51
00:03:09,760 --> 00:03:13,530
I realize that we have this idea of our invincibility

52
00:03:13,530 --> 00:03:16,400
and then we're struck with our mortality.

53
00:03:17,940 --> 00:03:19,840
Perhaps you know someone who has died recently.

54
00:03:20,480 --> 00:03:23,280
We all know somebody, and eventually it will be us.

55
00:03:24,380 --> 00:03:26,120
And we don't want to ponder our mortality.

56
00:03:26,200 --> 00:03:27,480
That's a dismal experience.

57
00:03:28,320 --> 00:03:31,240
We don't do it often, but world events, even currently,

58
00:03:32,080 --> 00:03:37,000
cause us to begin to grapple with these heavy and very real issues.

59
00:03:38,690 --> 00:03:42,770
But you know, every age struggles with the finality of the grave.

60
00:03:44,240 --> 00:03:48,260
And let's be honest, we live in a death-denying society.

61
00:03:49,250 --> 00:03:52,090
We simply put that away to professionals.

62
00:03:52,330 --> 00:03:56,530
We don't deal with it as a culture very well at all.

63
00:03:58,120 --> 00:04:00,460
In fact, we kind of sanitize the old experience.

64
00:04:01,420 --> 00:04:06,120
And especially in Orange County, we'd rather talk about tummy tucks and Botox

65
00:04:06,120 --> 00:04:10,580
instead of the grip of the grave and the reality therein.

66
00:04:10,880 --> 00:04:18,620
But no matter how we dress it up, the raw vulnerability of our lives is revealed

67
00:04:18,620 --> 00:04:20,500
when you walk through a cemetery.

68
00:04:22,120 --> 00:04:25,340
We're invincible until we walk through a cemetery.

69
00:04:25,480 --> 00:04:27,780
And you realize we're all going to be there someday.

70
00:04:29,260 --> 00:04:33,960
And we really have to grapple with our own struggle with death and our fear of death.

71
00:04:33,960 --> 00:04:39,660
In fact, the Bible speaks about this natural fear that human beings have about death.

72
00:04:40,530 --> 00:04:45,060
In Hebrews chapter 2, it says in verse 14 and 15,

73
00:04:45,780 --> 00:04:51,100
Because God's children are human beings made of flesh and blood,

74
00:04:51,620 --> 00:04:56,880
Jesus also became flesh and blood by being born in human form.

75
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:00,460
For only as a human being could he die.

76
00:05:00,460 --> 00:05:06,040
And only by dying could he break the power of the devil who had the power of death.

77
00:05:06,820 --> 00:05:14,440
Only in this way could he deliver those who have lived all their lives as slaves to the fear of dying.

78
00:05:16,510 --> 00:05:18,970
We live as slaves to fear of dying.

79
00:05:20,280 --> 00:05:26,200
And Jesus has come to break that spell, to break that fear, to give us hope.

80
00:05:28,220 --> 00:05:31,580
But dying is natural, and the fear of dying is natural for human beings.

81
00:05:32,580 --> 00:05:40,280
In a really remarkable book called Beyond Death by Gary Habermas and J.P. Moreland here of Talbot right next door,

82
00:05:40,720 --> 00:05:43,620
they describe four reasons why we fear death.

83
00:05:43,620 --> 00:05:45,580
And one of them is the potential for pain.

84
00:05:46,260 --> 00:05:47,060
And we do struggle.

85
00:05:47,060 --> 00:05:52,340
That's probably one of the most gripping parts of death is the fear of pain in the end.

86
00:05:53,590 --> 00:05:58,770
They also argue that saying goodbye to loved ones is a part of it that makes us deeply fear death.

87
00:06:00,310 --> 00:06:05,890
In addition to the apprehension of the unknown, what will happen when we come to the end?

88
00:06:07,790 --> 00:06:11,860
And for some, the fear of being alone, passing through that experience alone,

89
00:06:11,960 --> 00:06:13,820
and perhaps being alone on the other side.

90
00:06:15,340 --> 00:06:16,680
All of these are real.

91
00:06:16,840 --> 00:06:17,880
These are real fears.

92
00:06:17,880 --> 00:06:25,120
And if we get honest, many of us, most of us, all of us, carry these around to some degree or another in our souls.

93
00:06:25,460 --> 00:06:29,400
But, friends, there is hope to these issues.

94
00:06:29,960 --> 00:06:31,920
There is an answer.

95
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:39,300
And it will come into focus this morning as we look at this beautiful text from John chapter 11.

96
00:06:40,610 --> 00:06:42,050
And so we begin at verse 1.

97
00:06:43,490 --> 00:06:46,770
A man named Lazarus was sick.

98
00:06:48,920 --> 00:06:52,340
He lived in Bethany with his sisters, Mary and Martha.

99
00:06:53,500 --> 00:06:57,700
This is the Mary who poured the expensive perfume on the Lord's feet

100
00:06:57,700 --> 00:06:59,920
and wiped them with her hair.

101
00:07:01,350 --> 00:07:03,230
Her brother Lazarus was sick.

102
00:07:04,420 --> 00:07:07,540
So the two sisters sent a message to Jesus telling him,

103
00:07:07,540 --> 00:07:11,360
Lord, the one that you love is very sick.

104
00:07:13,180 --> 00:07:15,220
But when Jesus heard about it, he said,

105
00:07:16,280 --> 00:07:18,940
Lazarus' sickness will not end in death.

106
00:07:19,540 --> 00:07:22,500
No, it is for the glory of God.

107
00:07:23,530 --> 00:07:26,670
I, the Son of God, will receive glory from this.

108
00:07:28,330 --> 00:07:31,250
Although Jesus loved Mary and Martha and Lazarus,

109
00:07:31,910 --> 00:07:35,030
he stayed where he was for the next two days

110
00:07:35,030 --> 00:07:37,460
and did not go to them.

111
00:07:38,620 --> 00:07:40,860
Finally, after two days, he said to his disciples,

112
00:07:41,460 --> 00:07:43,240
let's go to Judea again.

113
00:07:45,300 --> 00:07:46,620
But his disciples objected.

114
00:07:46,620 --> 00:07:49,280
Teacher, they said, only a few days ago,

115
00:07:49,400 --> 00:07:51,660
the Jewish leaders in Judea were trying to kill you.

116
00:07:51,980 --> 00:07:53,820
Are you going to go there again?

117
00:07:55,510 --> 00:07:59,480
Jesus replied, there are 12 hours of daylight every day.

118
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:03,300
As long as it is light, people can walk safely.

119
00:08:04,120 --> 00:08:06,920
They can see because they have the light of this world.

120
00:08:07,420 --> 00:08:11,400
Only at night is there danger of stumbling because there is no light.

121
00:08:12,480 --> 00:08:18,740
And then he said, our friend Lazarus has fallen asleep, but now I will go and wake him up.

122
00:08:20,240 --> 00:08:23,300
The disciples said, Lord, if he's sleeping, that means he's going to get better.

123
00:08:24,630 --> 00:08:27,550
They thought Jesus meant Lazarus was having a good night's rest.

124
00:08:28,010 --> 00:08:30,850
But Jesus meant that Lazarus had died.

125
00:08:32,340 --> 00:08:34,600
And then he told them plainly, Lazarus is dead.

126
00:08:35,640 --> 00:08:37,660
And for your sake, I'm glad I wasn't there.

127
00:08:37,940 --> 00:08:41,820
Because this will give you the opportunity to believe in me.

128
00:08:42,560 --> 00:08:44,520
Come, let's go see him.

129
00:08:46,660 --> 00:08:49,200
Now Thomas, nicknamed the twin, said to his fellow disciples,

130
00:08:49,800 --> 00:08:51,680
yes, let's go too and die with Jesus.

131
00:08:52,320 --> 00:08:57,450
When Jesus arrived at Bethany, he was told that Lazarus had already been in his grave

132
00:08:57,450 --> 00:08:58,630
for four days.

133
00:09:00,160 --> 00:09:01,940
Bethany was only a few miles down the road

134
00:09:01,940 --> 00:09:04,140
from Jerusalem, and many of the people

135
00:09:04,140 --> 00:09:06,080
had come to pay their respects and console

136
00:09:06,080 --> 00:09:08,280
Martha and Mary on their loss.

137
00:09:09,240 --> 00:09:10,340
When Martha got word

138
00:09:10,340 --> 00:09:12,360
that Jesus was coming, she went to meet

139
00:09:12,360 --> 00:09:14,810
him, but Mary stayed at home.

140
00:09:15,910 --> 00:09:16,750
Martha said to Jesus,

141
00:09:16,950 --> 00:09:18,910
Lord, if you had been here,

142
00:09:19,650 --> 00:09:20,970
my brother would not have died.

143
00:09:22,340 --> 00:09:23,560
But even now, I know

144
00:09:23,560 --> 00:09:25,660
that God will give you whatever you ask.

145
00:09:27,160 --> 00:09:28,340
Jesus told her, your brother

146
00:09:28,340 --> 00:09:29,980
will rise again.

147
00:09:31,600 --> 00:09:34,500
Yes, Martha said, when everyone else rises on resurrection day.

148
00:09:35,630 --> 00:09:39,450
And Jesus told her, I am the resurrection and the life.

149
00:09:40,310 --> 00:09:45,110
Those who believe in me, even though they die like everyone else, will live again.

150
00:09:46,430 --> 00:09:51,250
They are given eternal life for believing in me and will never perish.

151
00:09:52,390 --> 00:09:53,710
Do you believe this, Martha?

152
00:09:55,440 --> 00:09:56,820
Yes, Lord, she told him.

153
00:09:57,660 --> 00:10:02,820
I've always believed you are the Messiah, the Son of God, the one who has come into the world from God.

154
00:10:03,960 --> 00:10:05,660
Then she left him and returned to Mary.

155
00:10:06,700 --> 00:10:08,740
She called Mary aside from the mourners and told her,

156
00:10:08,740 --> 00:10:11,820
the teacher is here and he wants to see you.

157
00:10:12,750 --> 00:10:14,330
So Mary immediately went to him.

158
00:10:15,650 --> 00:10:18,230
Now Jesus had stayed outside the village at the place where

159
00:10:18,230 --> 00:10:19,190
Martha met him.

160
00:10:20,120 --> 00:10:23,920
When the people who were at the house trying to console Mary saw

161
00:10:23,920 --> 00:10:26,820
her leave so hastily, they assumed she was going to

162
00:10:26,820 --> 00:10:28,080
Lazarus' grave to weep.

163
00:10:28,580 --> 00:10:29,660
So they followed her there.

164
00:10:30,920 --> 00:10:33,600
When Mary arrived and saw Jesus, she fell down at his feet

165
00:10:33,600 --> 00:10:37,340
and said, Lord, if you had been here, my brother would not have died.

166
00:10:38,520 --> 00:10:41,600
When Jesus saw her weeping and saw the other people wailing with her,

167
00:10:42,100 --> 00:10:45,620
he was moved with indignation and was deeply troubled.

168
00:10:47,240 --> 00:10:50,700
Where have you put him, he asked them. And they told him, Lord,

169
00:10:50,700 --> 00:10:56,830
come and see. And Jesus wept. The people who were standing

170
00:10:56,830 --> 00:10:59,830
nearby said how much he loved him.

171
00:11:01,100 --> 00:11:05,390
But some said this man healed a blind man. Why couldn't he keep Lazarus

172
00:11:05,390 --> 00:11:13,470
from dying. And again, Jesus was troubled deeply. Then they came to the grave. It was a cave with a

173
00:11:13,470 --> 00:11:21,990
stone rolled across the entrance. Roll the stone aside, Jesus told them. But Martha, dead man's

174
00:11:21,990 --> 00:11:26,610
sister, said, Lord, by now the smell will be terrible because he's been dead for four days.

175
00:11:28,060 --> 00:11:33,330
And Jesus responded, didn't I tell you that you will see God's glory if you believe?

176
00:11:33,330 --> 00:11:36,030
so they rolled the stone aside

177
00:11:36,030 --> 00:11:38,680
and Jesus looked up to heaven and said

178
00:11:38,680 --> 00:11:41,180
Father, thank you for hearing me

179
00:11:41,180 --> 00:11:43,060
you always hear me

180
00:11:43,060 --> 00:11:44,820
but I said it out loud

181
00:11:44,820 --> 00:11:47,100
for the sake of all these people standing here

182
00:11:47,100 --> 00:11:49,220
so that they will believe in me

183
00:11:49,220 --> 00:11:51,130
and Jesus shouted

184
00:11:51,130 --> 00:11:53,820
Lazarus, come out

185
00:11:53,820 --> 00:11:57,520
and Lazarus came out

186
00:11:57,520 --> 00:11:59,800
bound in grave clothes

187
00:11:59,800 --> 00:12:01,480
his face wrapped in a head cloth

188
00:12:01,480 --> 00:12:03,700
Jesus told him, unwrap him

189
00:12:03,700 --> 00:12:05,300
and let him go

190
00:12:07,840 --> 00:12:10,400
Well, many of the people who were there with Mary believed in Jesus,

191
00:12:10,520 --> 00:12:11,660
and when they saw this happen,

192
00:12:12,970 --> 00:12:16,610
but some went to the Pharisees and told them what Jesus had done.

193
00:12:17,460 --> 00:12:20,300
And the leading priests and the Pharisees called the high council together

194
00:12:20,300 --> 00:12:21,780
to discuss the situation.

195
00:12:23,440 --> 00:12:24,420
What are we going to do?

196
00:12:25,480 --> 00:12:26,260
They asked each other.

197
00:12:26,500 --> 00:12:29,100
This man certainly performs many miraculous signs.

198
00:12:29,100 --> 00:12:32,540
If we leave him alone, the whole nation will follow him,

199
00:12:33,440 --> 00:12:37,140
and then the Roman army will come and destroy both our temple and our nation.

200
00:12:37,140 --> 00:12:44,430
And one of them, Caiaphas, the high priest this year said, how can you be so stupid?

201
00:12:45,450 --> 00:12:47,450
Why should the whole nation be destroyed?

202
00:12:47,890 --> 00:12:51,170
Let this one man die for the people.

203
00:12:53,580 --> 00:12:58,500
This prophecy that Jesus should die for the entire nation came from Caiaphas in his position

204
00:12:58,500 --> 00:12:59,240
as high priest.

205
00:12:59,520 --> 00:13:00,840
He didn't think of it himself.

206
00:13:01,640 --> 00:13:03,360
He was inspired to say it.

207
00:13:04,350 --> 00:13:09,750
It was a prediction that Jesus' death would not be for Israel only, but for the gathering

208
00:13:09,750 --> 00:13:13,710
together of all the children of God scattered around the world.

209
00:13:15,280 --> 00:13:17,680
And so from that time on, Jewish leaders began to plot

210
00:13:17,680 --> 00:13:22,670
Jesus' death. And as a result, Jesus stopped his public ministry among the

211
00:13:22,670 --> 00:13:25,970
people and left Jerusalem. He went to a place near the wilderness

212
00:13:25,970 --> 00:13:30,350
to the village of Ephraim and stayed there with his disciples.

213
00:13:33,150 --> 00:13:35,730
This narrative describes the

214
00:13:35,730 --> 00:13:39,390
climactic event in the ministry of Jesus.

215
00:13:39,390 --> 00:13:46,480
This is the most dramatic, the most provocative miracle in the gospel at all.

216
00:13:47,650 --> 00:13:50,170
And it's life-changing for so many people here.

217
00:13:50,810 --> 00:13:53,370
For Lazarus, life-changing.

218
00:13:54,010 --> 00:13:59,600
For Mary, Martha, and even the extended family for Jesus.

219
00:14:00,420 --> 00:14:06,790
All these people, for Jesus' death, we're all going to get life.

220
00:14:07,750 --> 00:14:11,390
That's what the religious leaders began to pull out of this event.

221
00:14:12,220 --> 00:14:13,780
Friends, there's so much in this text.

222
00:14:13,900 --> 00:14:15,240
Let's unpack it for a few moments.

223
00:14:15,980 --> 00:14:19,100
The story begins with these three characters, Mary, Martha, and Lazarus,

224
00:14:19,520 --> 00:14:23,660
brothers and sisters to whom Jesus felt very close.

225
00:14:24,580 --> 00:14:28,400
Perhaps Mary, Martha, and Lazarus were almost like extended family to Jesus.

226
00:14:30,090 --> 00:14:32,390
Either way, Jesus cares for them so deeply.

227
00:14:34,200 --> 00:14:35,720
We heard about Lazarus' condition.

228
00:14:36,240 --> 00:14:39,900
He responds in a similar way to the blind man we saw last week,

229
00:14:40,060 --> 00:14:43,140
that God is going to be glorified in this event coming up.

230
00:14:43,280 --> 00:14:47,310
But what's interesting is Jesus does not go immediately.

231
00:14:48,640 --> 00:14:50,740
In fact, he waits two days.

232
00:14:52,150 --> 00:14:55,130
Jesus operates on his own time.

233
00:14:56,560 --> 00:14:57,500
There's a lesson for us.

234
00:14:57,800 --> 00:15:01,620
God operates on his own time.

235
00:15:02,990 --> 00:15:05,190
We may want things to happen in our time.

236
00:15:05,310 --> 00:15:07,510
God operates on his time.

237
00:15:09,890 --> 00:15:13,340
Finally, two days later, they head for Judea.

238
00:15:13,740 --> 00:15:16,420
And that must have been frightening to the disciples

239
00:15:16,420 --> 00:15:18,300
because there had been plots to kill Jesus.

240
00:15:18,940 --> 00:15:22,740
People had talked of killing Jesus, trying to arrest him, trying to stone him.

241
00:15:24,130 --> 00:15:26,470
So when Thomas speaks, well, let's go die with Jesus,

242
00:15:27,680 --> 00:15:29,700
he's got a good picture of what's happening there.

243
00:15:31,720 --> 00:15:32,900
And finally they head to Bethany.

244
00:15:34,020 --> 00:15:36,460
Now Lazarus has been dead for four days.

245
00:15:38,070 --> 00:15:39,610
What's so important about four days?

246
00:15:40,530 --> 00:15:43,050
It's actually very significant, four days.

247
00:15:43,110 --> 00:15:44,270
The author points that out.

248
00:15:44,750 --> 00:15:48,890
It was believed at the time that the soul of a dead person

249
00:15:48,890 --> 00:15:52,650
remained in the vicinity of the body for three days,

250
00:15:52,850 --> 00:15:54,230
hoping to reenter it.

251
00:15:55,650 --> 00:15:58,210
But once decomposition begins to set in,

252
00:15:58,790 --> 00:16:01,070
the soul was thought to have finally departed.

253
00:16:03,280 --> 00:16:07,410
What's happening here is it is very clear that he is dead.

254
00:16:09,050 --> 00:16:11,610
The soul is not trying to bring him alive again.

255
00:16:12,930 --> 00:16:14,110
Decomposition has begun.

256
00:16:14,210 --> 00:16:15,930
He is dead.

257
00:16:16,270 --> 00:16:18,430
There is no resuscitation going on here.

258
00:16:18,510 --> 00:16:21,510
There is no faint heartbeat that we can't pick up.

259
00:16:21,510 --> 00:16:23,870
this man is dead.

260
00:16:27,940 --> 00:16:29,000
Martha meets with Jesus

261
00:16:29,000 --> 00:16:32,390
and she knows that Jesus

262
00:16:32,390 --> 00:16:34,490
could have prevented her brother's death.

263
00:16:37,710 --> 00:16:38,830
Jesus says that Lazarus

264
00:16:38,830 --> 00:16:41,200
will rise again. She agrees.

265
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:42,360
Yes.

266
00:16:43,440 --> 00:16:44,420
She'd been taught that.

267
00:16:45,760 --> 00:16:47,820
She'd been taught at the end time that the Jews would be

268
00:16:47,820 --> 00:16:49,900
raised up at the end. But Jesus goes

269
00:16:49,900 --> 00:16:51,840
much further. He goes right to

270
00:16:51,840 --> 00:16:53,980
the punchline. You don't have to

271
00:16:53,980 --> 00:16:55,260
wait for the end.

272
00:16:56,420 --> 00:16:58,540
I am right now.

273
00:16:58,540 --> 00:17:00,980
resurrection and life.

274
00:17:01,440 --> 00:17:03,140
The one who believes in me

275
00:17:03,140 --> 00:17:05,020
even though he or she dies

276
00:17:05,020 --> 00:17:06,200
will live.

277
00:17:07,660 --> 00:17:09,640
And everyone who lives believing in me

278
00:17:09,640 --> 00:17:11,120
does not ultimately die at all.

279
00:17:12,310 --> 00:17:13,250
Do you believe this?

280
00:17:14,720 --> 00:17:15,400
What a claim.

281
00:17:16,220 --> 00:17:17,560
What a claim.

282
00:17:19,040 --> 00:17:20,820
To consider yourself the resurrection

283
00:17:20,820 --> 00:17:21,980
and the life.

284
00:17:22,200 --> 00:17:24,660
That is the most bold, audacious statement

285
00:17:24,660 --> 00:17:25,260
I have heard.

286
00:17:27,710 --> 00:17:30,210
Jesus is claiming to be in charge of everything.

287
00:17:30,370 --> 00:17:31,710
Life and death

288
00:17:31,710 --> 00:17:35,710
and everything in between, that's a bold statement.

289
00:17:39,580 --> 00:17:40,860
Let's go back in history a few years.

290
00:17:42,880 --> 00:17:46,560
A fighter named Cassius Clay, Muhammad Ali,

291
00:17:47,710 --> 00:17:52,070
claimed that he was the best boxer

292
00:17:52,070 --> 00:17:53,350
to ever step on the planet.

293
00:17:55,610 --> 00:17:57,190
And then he set out and defeated

294
00:17:57,190 --> 00:17:59,920
this gentleman, Sonny Liston.

295
00:18:01,480 --> 00:18:04,780
And after he took him down, in an interview later,

296
00:18:04,860 --> 00:18:06,880
he said this deeply philosophical truth.

297
00:18:06,960 --> 00:18:10,080
He said, it ain't bragging if you got the goods.

298
00:18:14,530 --> 00:18:17,250
Jesus said, I'm the resurrection and the life.

299
00:18:18,710 --> 00:18:20,810
That's not bragging if you got the goods.

300
00:18:22,000 --> 00:18:24,940
Jesus has the goods.

301
00:18:26,500 --> 00:18:33,240
That's the most outrageous claim to be the resurrection and the life unless he has the goods.

302
00:18:35,220 --> 00:18:36,280
And what happens next?

303
00:18:36,980 --> 00:18:37,740
He has the goods.

304
00:18:39,720 --> 00:18:40,520
They took him to the tomb.

305
00:18:41,730 --> 00:18:43,130
Jesus speaks a prayer to the Father.

306
00:18:43,250 --> 00:18:43,890
They all can hear.

307
00:18:43,890 --> 00:18:53,040
And then in front of the supporters, the detractors, and all the curiosity seekers, they saw what's not supposed to happen.

308
00:18:53,500 --> 00:18:57,870
Truly, a dead man walked out of a tomb.

309
00:18:59,090 --> 00:18:59,590
Can't be.

310
00:18:59,970 --> 00:19:00,710
Can't be.

311
00:19:01,150 --> 00:19:02,510
You could just see them rubbing their eyes.

312
00:19:02,810 --> 00:19:04,850
This cannot be.

313
00:19:06,260 --> 00:19:08,220
But a dead man came up from the grave.

314
00:19:08,520 --> 00:19:11,040
Friends, that is power.

315
00:19:14,800 --> 00:19:19,260
And you can just see Lazarus standing there like a mummy, wrapped from head to toe.

316
00:19:20,330 --> 00:19:22,890
The most spectacular miracle of Jesus' ministry.

317
00:19:25,360 --> 00:19:27,620
Unwrap him, Jesus says, and let him go.

318
00:19:29,480 --> 00:19:34,180
Now in the context of Jewish laws that regarded dead bodies as unclean,

319
00:19:34,180 --> 00:19:36,360
you can just imagine the questions.

320
00:19:36,940 --> 00:19:37,660
Do we touch him?

321
00:19:38,270 --> 00:19:39,670
Do we go near him?

322
00:19:40,950 --> 00:19:45,830
And it's not written, but I surmise there was a further conversation that only the minimal words that we see.

323
00:19:45,830 --> 00:19:51,670
I can even imagine Jesus approaching Lazarus and embracing him.

324
00:19:52,970 --> 00:19:55,890
And you can imagine the Jewish leaders just about passing out.

325
00:19:56,630 --> 00:19:57,530
This cannot be.

326
00:19:58,630 --> 00:20:00,510
You don't touch untouchables like that.

327
00:20:01,920 --> 00:20:03,360
Jesus would embrace him.

328
00:20:05,190 --> 00:20:06,830
What would you have said if you stood there?

329
00:20:08,660 --> 00:20:09,500
Would you believe it?

330
00:20:10,890 --> 00:20:11,650
Would you believe it?

331
00:20:13,620 --> 00:20:15,360
What do you say about Jesus today?

332
00:20:17,100 --> 00:20:17,940
Do you believe it?

333
00:20:19,120 --> 00:20:19,800
Do you believe it?

334
00:20:21,740 --> 00:20:26,820
The raising of Lazarus is the sign that Jesus is the one who gives life.

335
00:20:28,840 --> 00:20:29,780
But some didn't believe.

336
00:20:30,660 --> 00:20:33,990
Sadly, some still said, we're not going to believe.

337
00:20:34,110 --> 00:20:40,410
Even with the mummy standing with the head graves and the clothes wrapped around him,

338
00:20:40,430 --> 00:20:41,490
they still wouldn't believe it.

339
00:20:41,550 --> 00:20:43,310
And they went off and they plotted against him.

340
00:20:47,690 --> 00:20:48,270
Do you believe it?

341
00:20:50,040 --> 00:20:51,480
And friends, it's more than just a doctrine.

342
00:20:51,480 --> 00:20:56,620
It's more than just believing in Jesus that he can do things like that.

343
00:20:56,620 --> 00:21:00,500
It's about knowing this Jesus who saves us.

344
00:21:00,760 --> 00:21:01,740
It's not a doctrine.

345
00:21:02,060 --> 00:21:06,080
It's a relationship with the man who did this.

346
00:21:08,890 --> 00:21:15,390
To face death with confidence, friends, we have to know Jesus, not just know about Jesus.

347
00:21:17,090 --> 00:21:19,110
This is not about a textbook discussion.

348
00:21:19,670 --> 00:21:25,710
This is engaging in a relationship with the risen Lord who is alive today

349
00:21:25,710 --> 00:21:30,470
and can be in relationship with you each and every moment of every day.

350
00:21:30,650 --> 00:21:31,450
Do you believe it?

351
00:21:34,240 --> 00:21:39,480
And if you know Jesus, then there's no need to fear death.

352
00:21:40,480 --> 00:21:42,860
There's no need to fear death.

353
00:21:44,370 --> 00:21:49,510
Followers of Jesus have no need to fear death because Jesus is the Lord over death.

354
00:21:49,510 --> 00:21:51,990
He conquered death in his own resurrection,

355
00:21:52,530 --> 00:21:57,430
and he displays that kind of power publicly in the raising of Lazarus.

356
00:21:58,780 --> 00:21:59,860
We have no need to fear death.

357
00:21:59,860 --> 00:22:03,790
couple that with Paul's discussion about our bodies

358
00:22:03,790 --> 00:22:07,650
we have real hope to look forward to notice this verse

359
00:22:07,650 --> 00:22:11,100
from 2nd Corinthians chapter 5

360
00:22:11,100 --> 00:22:14,780
Paul writes for we know that when this earthly tent

361
00:22:14,780 --> 00:22:17,980
we live in is taken down when we die

362
00:22:17,980 --> 00:22:20,880
and leave these bodies we will have a home

363
00:22:20,880 --> 00:22:23,900
in heaven an eternal body made for us by

364
00:22:23,900 --> 00:22:26,800
God himself and not by human hands

365
00:22:26,800 --> 00:22:30,180
we grow weary in our present bodies

366
00:22:30,180 --> 00:22:32,620
and we long for the day

367
00:22:32,620 --> 00:22:35,380
when we will put on our heavenly bodies

368
00:22:35,380 --> 00:22:36,600
like new clothing

369
00:22:36,600 --> 00:22:39,970
for we will not be spirits without bodies

370
00:22:39,970 --> 00:22:42,570
but we will put on new heavenly bodies.

371
00:22:43,780 --> 00:22:46,480
Our dying bodies make us groan and sigh

372
00:22:46,480 --> 00:22:48,820
but it's not that we want to die

373
00:22:48,820 --> 00:22:50,040
and we have no bodies at all.

374
00:22:50,320 --> 00:22:52,740
We want to slip into our new bodies

375
00:22:52,740 --> 00:22:54,820
so that these dying bodies

376
00:22:54,820 --> 00:22:57,560
will be swallowed up by everlasting life.

377
00:22:58,560 --> 00:23:00,500
God himself has prepared us for this

378
00:23:00,500 --> 00:23:04,120
and as a guarantee, he has given us his Holy Spirit.

379
00:23:06,120 --> 00:23:08,860
Remember that list we gave of the reasons to fear death?

380
00:23:10,210 --> 00:23:11,290
The potential of pain.

381
00:23:12,570 --> 00:23:15,310
There is obviously always the potential for pain,

382
00:23:16,460 --> 00:23:19,580
but what helps me recognize and deal with that fact

383
00:23:19,580 --> 00:23:23,360
is that Jesus endured the most excruciating pain on the cross

384
00:23:23,360 --> 00:23:27,980
and realized that pain is only temporary,

385
00:23:28,800 --> 00:23:29,820
if there's pain at all.

386
00:23:31,400 --> 00:23:33,780
That fear of saying goodbye to loved ones.

387
00:23:35,060 --> 00:23:36,700
Friends, as Christians, once we die,

388
00:23:36,820 --> 00:23:38,820
we will be at home with the Lord, says the Scriptures,

389
00:23:39,220 --> 00:23:42,320
and then we're going to be resurrected on the last day.

390
00:23:43,540 --> 00:23:46,340
We will be with all of those who follow Jesus Christ.

391
00:23:46,720 --> 00:23:49,520
You will see your loved ones who are in Christ again.

392
00:23:50,600 --> 00:23:52,120
You will not be separated from them.

393
00:23:54,410 --> 00:23:56,450
The apprehension of the unknown was a fear.

394
00:23:58,330 --> 00:24:00,390
Jesus brought a man back from the grave.

395
00:24:01,520 --> 00:24:05,120
Jesus himself later went to the other side of the grave

396
00:24:05,120 --> 00:24:06,440
and came back.

397
00:24:08,010 --> 00:24:08,950
And while on the cross,

398
00:24:09,090 --> 00:24:10,470
Jesus even said to the thief

399
00:24:10,470 --> 00:24:11,550
hanging beside him,

400
00:24:13,000 --> 00:24:14,940
he said that you would be in paradise

401
00:24:14,940 --> 00:24:16,500
this very day with me.

402
00:24:18,530 --> 00:24:20,410
We can know what happens after death.

403
00:24:21,630 --> 00:24:23,830
We have nothing to fear

404
00:24:23,830 --> 00:24:27,350
from the fear of being alone.

405
00:24:28,780 --> 00:24:29,580
The fear of being alone

406
00:24:29,580 --> 00:24:31,260
is a real fear from our perspective

407
00:24:31,260 --> 00:24:32,340
that when you understand

408
00:24:32,340 --> 00:24:33,360
that you're going to be with Jesus,

409
00:24:33,640 --> 00:24:34,360
he will be there

410
00:24:34,360 --> 00:24:35,400
on the other side of the grave.

411
00:24:35,700 --> 00:24:36,460
You will be with those

412
00:24:36,460 --> 00:24:37,260
who are in Christ.

413
00:24:37,500 --> 00:24:38,520
You will not be alone.

414
00:24:39,000 --> 00:24:43,260
Jesus conquers these fears that we carry around.

415
00:24:46,280 --> 00:24:47,180
Amen to that.

416
00:24:48,590 --> 00:24:49,610
Christians, we have hope.

417
00:24:52,040 --> 00:24:55,980
And of all the philosophies in the world, none answers the issue of death like Jesus Christ.

418
00:24:57,850 --> 00:25:00,930
Nothing explains it like this.

419
00:25:01,070 --> 00:25:02,630
Nothing deals with it like this.

420
00:25:03,070 --> 00:25:10,340
Because no other philosophers have died and come back and raised others and promised that we'll be raised as well.

421
00:25:11,140 --> 00:25:15,730
Number two, and finally, knowing Jesus, there's Christ's power in your life today.

422
00:25:17,740 --> 00:25:20,640
Jesus does not say that he can provide resurrection and life.

423
00:25:20,960 --> 00:25:25,140
He says he is resurrection and life.

424
00:25:26,420 --> 00:25:31,900
Resurrection and life are aspects of what it means to live in intimate communion with Jesus.

425
00:25:33,410 --> 00:25:37,430
If Jesus is life, then those who believe in him will enjoy the confidence

426
00:25:37,430 --> 00:25:41,130
that we can have power over death as we know Jesus.

427
00:25:42,780 --> 00:25:44,880
And friends, you can have that kind of life now.

428
00:25:44,880 --> 00:25:47,930
there's real power available

429
00:25:47,930 --> 00:25:49,610
in the experience

430
00:25:49,610 --> 00:25:51,230
of Jesus Christ

431
00:25:51,230 --> 00:25:54,440
the power of God in our lives today

432
00:25:54,440 --> 00:25:56,300
is the same as the power

433
00:25:56,300 --> 00:25:58,140
that raised Jesus from the dead

434
00:25:58,140 --> 00:25:59,720
and Lazarus as well

435
00:25:59,720 --> 00:26:02,260
and that the same power we have access to today

436
00:26:02,260 --> 00:26:04,640
is the same power that enables us

437
00:26:04,640 --> 00:26:06,020
to live for eternity

438
00:26:06,020 --> 00:26:10,970
there's power in knowing Jesus

439
00:26:10,970 --> 00:26:13,780
there's power for

440
00:26:13,780 --> 00:26:15,620
living a life of purpose

441
00:26:15,620 --> 00:26:19,930
in knowing Jesus

442
00:26:19,930 --> 00:26:21,290
the resurrection, and the life.

443
00:26:21,570 --> 00:26:23,330
There is power for living a life

444
00:26:23,330 --> 00:26:25,470
free of addictions of this earth.

445
00:26:29,640 --> 00:26:31,060
In knowing Jesus personally,

446
00:26:31,160 --> 00:26:32,820
there's power for living a life

447
00:26:32,820 --> 00:26:34,100
free of fear.

448
00:26:36,550 --> 00:26:38,950
There's power for living a life of peace

449
00:26:38,950 --> 00:26:40,610
in the midst of chaos.

450
00:26:42,080 --> 00:26:43,420
We don't know what's going to happen

451
00:26:43,420 --> 00:26:44,920
in our world from moment to moment.

452
00:26:46,230 --> 00:26:47,530
But Christians, we have hope

453
00:26:47,530 --> 00:26:49,700
in the midst of chaos

454
00:26:49,700 --> 00:26:53,020
because of the power of Jesus Christ

455
00:26:53,020 --> 00:26:53,640
in our lives.

456
00:26:54,300 --> 00:26:55,580
Let's never forget

457
00:26:55,580 --> 00:26:57,800
we have hope in the midst of chaos

458
00:26:57,800 --> 00:27:01,090
and there's power for living

459
00:27:01,090 --> 00:27:03,070
a life of surrender to Jesus

460
00:27:03,070 --> 00:27:05,490
for his love for us

461
00:27:05,490 --> 00:27:06,590
is unquenchable

462
00:27:06,590 --> 00:27:10,650
I just want to celebrate the end

463
00:27:10,650 --> 00:27:12,850
